{
  "text": "Geminin, another important interaction factor of the BAF complex, is also highly expressed in early embryonic neural precursor cells in Xenopus [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . There is increasing evidence for the active involvement of Geminin in the induction of Sox2 expression through an SWI/SNF-dependent mechanism during vertebrate early neural development (17-19, 21, 34) . Interestingly, co-IP experiments showed that Akirin2, but not Akirin1, pulled down Geminin and vice versa (Fig. 5, A and B) . To define interacting regions within Akirin2 and Geminin, a series of the Akirin1-Akirin2 fusion constructs ",
